In that case, we can create a custom implementation for `navigator.clipboard.writeText` by using the `Object.defineProperty` method. Here's an updated example that demonstrates how to mock `navigator.clipboard.writeText` using `Object.defineProperty`:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { render, fireEvent, waitFor, act } from '@testing-library/react';
import App from './App';

describe('App', () => {
  it('should call navigator.clipboard.writeText', async () => {
    const writeTextMock = jest.fn();
    const originalWriteText = window.navigator.clipboard.writeText;

    // Mock writeText using Object.defineProperty
    Object.defineProperty(navigator.clipboard, 'writeText', {
      value: writeTextMock,
    });

    const { getByTestId } = render(<App />);
    const button = getByTestId('your-button-test-id');
    fireEvent.click(button);

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(writeTextMock).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
      expect(writeTextMock).toHaveBeenCalledWith('text-to-copy');
    });

    // Restore the original writeText function
    Object.defineProperty(navigator.clipboard, 'writeText', {
      value: originalWriteText,
    });
  });
});
```

In this updated example, we save a reference to the original `window.navigator.clipboard.writeText` function. Then, we use `Object.defineProperty` to define a new property `writeText` on `navigator.clipboard` and assign it the value of our mock function `writeTextMock`.

Inside the test, we render the app, simulate a button click, and assert that `writeTextMock` is called exactly once and with the expected argument.

Finally, to ensure that the original `writeText` function is restored, we use `Object.defineProperty` again to redefine the `writeText` property on `navigator.clipboard` and assign it the original function.

Please replace `'your-button-test-id'` with the actual test id of your button element, and `'text-to-copy'` with the actual text that you expect to be passed to `navigator.clipboard.writeText`.

If you're seeing the error message "Exceeded timeout of 5000 ms for a test," it means that the test is taking longer than the default timeout value in Jest, which is 5000 milliseconds (5 seconds). To resolve this issue, you can increase the timeout value using the `jest.setTimeout` method.

Here's how you can update your test to increase the timeout value:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { render, fireEvent, waitFor, act } from '@testing-library/react';
import App from './App';

describe('App', () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    jest.setTimeout(10000); // Set the timeout value to 10000 milliseconds (10 seconds)
  });

  afterEach(() => {
    jest.restoreAllMocks();
  });

  it('should call navigator.clipboard.writeText', async () => {
    // Test implementation...
  });
});
```

In this example, we use `jest.setTimeout` in the `beforeEach` hook to set the new timeout value to 10000 milliseconds (10 seconds). This allows the test to have sufficient time to complete without triggering the timeout error.

Please note that you can adjust the timeout value to fit the needs of your particular test case. Keep in mind that longer timeouts may increase the overall test suite execution time.

If you're still encountering the "Exceeded timeout" error message even after increasing the timeout value, another possible solution is to use `await` within the test to ensure that the asynchronous operation is fully completed before moving on. 

Here's an updated example illustrating the usage of `await`:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { render, fireEvent, act } from '@testing-library/react';
import App from './App';

describe('App', () => {
  it('should call navigator.clipboard.writeText', async () => {
    const writeTextMock = jest.fn();

    jest.spyOn(navigator.clipboard, 'writeText').mockImplementation(writeTextMock);

    const { getByTestId } = render(<App />);
    const button = getByTestId('your-button-test-id');
    fireEvent.click(button);

    await act(async () => {
      await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, 0));
    });

    expect(writeTextMock).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
    expect(writeTextMock).toHaveBeenCalledWith('text-to-copy');
  });
});
```

In this updated example, `act` from the `@testing-library/react` package has been used to wrap the asynchronous operations. The `act` function ensures that all pending promises are resolved before moving on to the expectations.

Additionally, we've introduced a `setTimeout` function with a delay of `0` to allow any pending promises or microtasks to be executed. This ensures that the asynchronous operation simulated by the button click has ample time to complete.

Please replace `'your-button-test-id'` with the actual test id of your button element, and `'text-to-copy'` with the actual text that you expect to be passed to `navigator.clipboard.writeText`. Give this updated test a try, and it should prevent the "Exceeded timeout" error.

To enable the `--trace-warnings` flag when running Jest, you will need to update the Jest configuration in your project.

In your project's `package.json` file, you can configure Jest to include the `--trace-warnings` flag by modifying the `jest` section as follows:

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "test": "jest"
  },
  "jest": {
    "verbose": true,
    "nodeArgs": ["--trace-warnings"]
  }
}
```

In the above example, the `nodeArgs` property is added to the Jest configuration with the value `["--trace-warnings"]`. This will pass the `--trace-warnings` flag to the Node.js runtime when executing Jest.

Once you've made this configuration change, you can run your tests using `npm test`
